At 04:37 AM 08/11/01, you wrote:

&gt;The reason I want to have a oneTimeSetup() and oneTimeTearDown() is to have
&gt;the ability to create an extensive directory/file creation for a class that
&gt;operates on directories and files.  I have found it takes to much time to
&gt;create/destroy the exact same &#39;data set&#39; for each test.  It works fine if
&gt;I use setUp and tearDown but I prefer to not take that time during development
&gt;test runs.


Couldn&#39;t you do this using ant - set the stuff up, run the unit tests, tear 
it down again.




&gt;jeb
&gt;
&gt;-- Original Message --
&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; setUp and tear down are used for each testcase, but it would be enough
&gt; &gt;&gt; to run them once. There is an example in the FAQ but I couldn&#39;t find
&gt; &gt;&gt; out, how to get it running.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;The rationale of the system is that each test must be independent of others.
&gt; &gt;That&#39;s why setUp() and tearDown() are called for each single test case.
&gt; &gt;Why
&gt; &gt;do you want to setUp and tearDown your text fixture only once?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;Anyway, if you really want to do this you can do either of these two ugly
&gt; &gt;things:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;- Write your own testSetUp() method as the first test method in the class
&gt; &gt;and testTearDown() as the last test method in the class. Pretty ugly, but
&gt; &gt;it
&gt; &gt;should work. I didn&#39;t try it myself, so I&#39;m not 100% sure it will.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;- If tearDown() is not really necessary, you can declare a static test
&gt; &gt;fixture and initialize it at the point of definition:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;public class InformationDirectoryTest extends TestCase {
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  private static SomeClass obj = new SomeClass();
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  &lt;tests&gt;
&gt; &gt;}
